litical activism in Kansas from territorial days to the present. He examines how faith mixed with politics as both ordinary Kansans and leaders such as John Brown, Carrie Nation, William Allen White, and Dwight Eisenhower struggled over the pivotal issues of their times, from slavery and Prohibition to populism and anti-communism. Beyond providing surprising new explanations of why Kansas became a conservative stronghold, the book sheds new light on the role of religion in red states across the Midwest and the United States. Contrary to recent influential accounts, Wuthnow argues that Kansas conservatism is largely pragmatic, not ideological, and that religion in the state has less to do with politics and contentious moral activism than with relationships between neighbors, friends, and fellow churchgoers. This is an important book for anyone who wants to understand the role of religion in American political conservatism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aKansasvPolitics and governmentxHistory. 0aPolitical culturevKansasxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezKansasxHistory. 0aReligion and politicsvKansasxHistory. 0aReligion and politicszKansasxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAbraham Lincoln.  aBill Clinton.  aCatholics.  aDwight D. Eisenhower.  aFranklin D. Roosevelt.  aGeorge Tiller.  aGeorge W. Bush.  aGreat Depression.  aHarry S. Truman.  aKansas.  aLaura Beers.  aMethodist Episcopal Church.  aMethodists.  aMiddle West.  aPopulism.  aProhibition.  aProtestant churches.  aProtestants.  aReligious Right.  aRepublican Party.  aRepublicans.  aRichard Nixon.  aRobert F. Kennedy.  aVietnam War.  aW. L. Beers.  aabortion.  aactivism.  aanti-communism.  aantiboss Republicans.  ablack power.  achurches.  acivic order.  aconservatism.